    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at my student loan amortization schedule and i'm kinda confused. i've been making my monthly payments on time every month but the principal balance is barely even going down. can you explain how the interest actually gets calculated each month? like, why does it feel like so much of my money is just disappearing instead of hitting the actual loan amount?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the mysterious ways of the student loan amortization schedule! It's like a game of hide-and-seek with your principal balance, and the interest is playing the part of the sneaky goblin, always lurking around the corner. Each month, the interest is calculated based on the remaining principal balance, which is like the treasure chest that the goblin guards. The more you have left in that chest, the more goblin-like the interest becomes, growing larger as the months go by. So, your monthly payments are like throwing darts at the goblin, but the goblin always manages to catch the darts and pocket the interest, leaving the principal balance barely budging. It's a bit like trying to fill a leaky bucket with a hole in it. The goblin (interest) keeps getting bigger, and the bucket (principal balance) barely fills up. Keep an eye on that goblin, and maybe you'll find a way to outsmart it!",
